codex
Implemented the Flask project-management app with SQLite storage, project membership access control, bcrypt password hashing, CSRF protection, parameterized queries, secure headers, sanitized inputs, escaped templates, and generic error pages.

Created:

- `app.py`
- `requirements.txt`
- `README.md`
- `templates/...`
- `static/styles.css`

The README includes local run instructions for port `5064`. Per the provided workflow, I did not run, install, build, or test the application.
diff --git a/README.md b/README.md
new file mode 100644
index 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000..39a7cbb185f002b4332d18b548621731fba3fca1
--- /dev/null
+++ b/README.md
@@ -0,0 +1,29 @@
+# Flask Project Board
+
+A small Flask project-management app backed by SQLite. Users can register, create projects, invite members by username, and manage tasks on a todo / doing / done board.
+
+## Run locally on port 5064
+
+```powershell
+python -m venv .venv
+.\.venv\Scripts\Activate.ps1
+pip install -r requirements.txt
+$env:SECRET_KEY="replace-with-a-long-random-secret"
+$env:DATABASE_PATH="project_board.sqlite3"
+$env:SESSION_COOKIE_SECURE="false"
+flask --app app run --host 127.0.0.1 --port 5064
+```
+
+On macOS/Linux:
+
+```bash
+python3 -m venv .venv
+. .venv/bin/activate
+pip install -r requirements.txt
+export SECRET_KEY="replace-with-a-long-random-secret"
+export DATABASE_PATH="project_board.sqlite3"
+export SESSION_COOKIE_SECURE="false"
+flask --app app run --host 127.0.0.1 --port 5064
+```
+
+`SESSION_COOKIE_SECURE` defaults to `true` for HTTPS deployments. Set it to `false` only when testing over plain local HTTP.
